8. 2-3. quem. quia. quod. etc.: an excellent example of the important principle of ‘suspension of clauses.' Any clause, principal or subordinate, is suspended when any subordinate connective appears between the first and last words of that clause: and the rest of the clause does not appear until the whole of the subordinate clause is finished. Here we have three clauses: quem non timeo, quia murus interest, quod semper volui, and the suspension may be indicated best by different types: QUEM.
